Baked Ziti with Vegetables and Mushrooms  (Cooking Light, March 2001, p. 128)

1 tbsp. vegetable oil
1 c. chopped onion
1 c. chopped green bell pepper
1 c. chopped red bell pepper
1.5 c. chopped portobello, cremini,
       or button mushroom
4 garlic cloves, chopped
1 tsp. dried basil
1/2 tsp. salt
1/4 tsp. black pepper
1 14.5 oz. can stewed tomatoes,
  undrained and chopped
1 8 oz. can tomato sauce
7 c. torn spinach (about 1.2 lb)
3 c. hot cooked ziti (about 2 1/4 c.
     uncooked short tube-shaped pasta)
cooking spray
1 c. part-skim ricotta cheese
1/2 c. (1 oz.) grated parmesan

Preheat oven to 375 degrees.

Heat oil in a large nonstick skillet over medium-high heat.
Add onion and bell peppers, and saute 5 minutes.  Add
mushrooms and garlic; saute 2 minutes.  Stir in basil,
salt, black pepper, tomatoes, and tomato sause, and bring
to a boil.  Reduce heat; simmer 5 minutes or until slightly
thick.  Stir in spinach; cook 1 minute or until spinach
wilts.  Stir in pasta.  Spoon into a 13x9-inch baking dish
coated with cooking spray.  Dollop with ricotta.

Cover and bake at 375 degrees for 20 minutes.  Uncover;
sprinkle with Parmesan.  Bake an additional 5 minutes or
until lightly browned.

Yield 8 servings.

Note: To make ahead, assemble casserole as directed.  Cover
and refrigerate overnight.  Let stand 30 minutes at room
temperature, and bake as directed.
